Background & Context¶

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, you have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. For example, if the business knows the market price, it will never sell anything below it.

Objective¶

Explore and visualize the dataset.
Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.
Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data Dictionary¶

S.No. : Serial Number
Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name
Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase Cities
Year : Manufacturing year of the car
Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM.
Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car. (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car. (Automatic / Manual)
Owner : Type of ownership
Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC.
Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp.
Seats : The number of seats in the car.
New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs.(1 Lakh = 100, 000)
Price : The price of the used car in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100, 000)

Fix Data Types¶

  1. Of the 14 Variables, 3 are Integers and 2 of Float data type which are valid data types except for 9 remaining variables of object string data type.

  2. Name, Location,Fuel_Type, Transmission and Owner_Type are of object type. These will be converted to category data type.

  3. Year will also be converted to categorical variable since we cannot say a year is greater than the other.

  4. Mileage,Engine, Power and New_Price are numerical in value but are strings. We would need to strip them of units and convert them to real numerical values for further analysis

In [16]:
def mile_to_num(mile_val):
    """This function takes in a string representing Mileage in 'km/kg' or 'kmpl'
    and converts it to a number.
    If the input is already numeric, which probably means it's NaN,
    this function just returns np.nan."""
    if isinstance(mile_val, str):  # checks if `mile_val` is a string
        multiplier = 1  # handles the km/kg and kmpl units
        if mile_val.endswith('km/kg'):
            multiplier = 1
        elif mile_val.endswith('kmpl'):
            multiplier = 1
            return float(mile_val.replace('km/kg', '').replace('kmpl', '')) * multiplier
    else:  # this happens when the current mileage is np.nan
        return np.nan

for colname in mile_col:
    c_d[colname] = c_d[colname].apply(mile_to_num)

def pe_to_num(pe_val):
    """This function takes in a string representing enteries for Power or Engine  in 'bhp' or 'CC'
    and converts it to a number.
    If the input is already numeric, which probably means it's NaN,
    this function just returns np.nan."""
    if isinstance(pe_val, str):  # checks if `PE_val` is a string
        multiplier = 1  # handles the bhp and CC units
        if pe_val.endswith('bhp'):
            multiplier = 1
        elif pe_val.endswith('CC'):
            multiplier = 1
        return float(pe_val.replace('bhp', '').replace('CC', '')) * multiplier
    else:  # this happens when the current value is np.nan
        return np.nan

for colname in PE_col:
    c_d[colname] = c_d[colname].apply(pe_to_num)

# While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency 
# and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(14,9), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (10,9))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='pink') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='yellow', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.

def perc_on_bar(plot, feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # height of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 14) # annotate the percantage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

In [67]:
# Lets treat outliers by flooring and capping
def treat_outliers(c_d,col):
    '''
    treats outliers in a varaible
    col: str, name of the numerical varaible
    c_d: data frame
    col: name of the column
    '''
    Q1=c_d[col].quantile(0.25) # 25th quantile
    Q3=c_d[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR=Q3-Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5*IQR 
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    c_d[col] = np.clip(c_d[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker) # all the values samller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned value of Lower_whisker 
                                                            # and all the values above upper_whishker will be assigned value of upper_Whisker 
    return c_d

def treat_outliers_all(c_d, col_list):
    '''
    treat outlier in all numerical varaibles
    col_list: list of numerical varaibles
    df: data frame
    '''
    for c in col_list:
        c_d = treat_outliers(c_d,c)
        
    return c_d

Observations¶

  • Assuming a confidence level of 0.05 (5%), then any variable with p-values less than 0.05 would be considered significant.
  • A negative coefficient implies Price deceases with their increase.
  • A positive coefficient implies Price inceases with their increase.
  • Multicollinearity affects the p values, we will treat multicollinearity per p values

Interpreting the Regression Results:¶

  1. Adjusted. R-squared: It reflects the fit of the model.
    • R-squared values range from 0 to 1, where a higher value generally indicates a better fit, assuming certain conditions are met.
    • In our case, the value for Adj. R-squared is 0.915, which is good!

  2. const coefficient is the Y-intercept.

    • It means that if all the dependent variables (features: like Age,Power, Engine, Transmission, Fuel_Type and so on..) coefficients are zero, then the expected output (i.e., the Y) would be equal to the const coefficient.
    • In our case, the value for const coeff is 6.95

  3. Schooling coeff: It represents the change in the output Y due to a change of one unit in the Schooling (everything else held constant).

  4. std err: It reflects the level of accuracy of the coefficients.
    • The lower it is, the higher is the level of accuracy.

  5. P >|t|: It is p-value.

    • Pr(>|t|) : For each independent feature there is a null hypothesis and alternate hypothesis

      Ho : Independent feature is not significant

      Ha : Independent feature is that it is significant

Pr(>|t|) gives P-value for each independent feature to check that null hypothesis. we are considering 0.05 (5%) as significance level

  • A p-value of less than 0.05 is considered to be statistically significant.
    1. Confidence Interval: It represents the range in which our coefficients are likely to fall (with a likelihood of 95%).

Testing the Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  1. No Multicollinearity
  2. Mean of residuals should be 0
  3. No Heteroscedacity
  4. Linearity of variables
  5. Normality of error terms

Observation¶

As seen, many of the VIF scores are greater than 5.To remove Multicollinearity, the following steps are engaged,

  1. Drop every column one by one, that has VIF score greater than 5.
  2. Look at the adjusted R square of all these models
  3. Drop the Variable that makes least change in Adjusted-R square
  4. Check the VIF Scores again
  5. Continue till you get all VIF scores under 5

TEST FOR LINEARITY¶
  1. Linearity describes a straight-line relationship between two variables, predictor variables must have a linear relation with the dependent variable.
  2. Make a plot of fitted values vs Residuals, if they don’t follow any pattern, then we say the model is linear otherwise model is showing signs of non-linearity.
  3. We will transform the variables and make the relationships linear
In [90]:

Scatter plot shows the distribution of residuals (errors) vs fitted values (predicted values) - There exists no patterns in this plot, we consider it as signs of non-linearity in the data and a pattern means that the model doesn’t capture non-linear effects. No pattern in residual hence 1st assumptions is satisfied

  1. The residuals are not normal as per shapiro test, but as per QQ plot they are approximately normal.
  2. The issue with shapiro test is when dataset is big, even for small deviations, it shows data as not normal
  3. Hence we go with QQ plot and say that residuals are normal
  4. We can try to treat data for outliers and see if that helps in further normalising the residual curve

TEST FOR HOMOSCEDASTICITY¶

Null hypothesis : Residuals are homoscedastic

Alternate hypothesis : Residuals have hetroscedasticity

Observations¶

Now this is our final model which follows all the assumptions and this can be used for interpretations¶

  1. Kilometer Driven and Age rates come out to be very signifcant, as expected. As they increase, the Price decreases, as visible in the negative coeefficient
  2. A 1 unit increase in Manual Transmission Type,leads to a decrease in Price by 1.0162
  3. Equally, any increase in a unit of the second owner type and third owner type respectively leds to a decrease in Price
  4. Engine and Power have a very strong effect on Price as an increase in the Brake Horse power and the Engine Capacity apparently increase the Price of the vehicle
  5. An increase in any unit of the FuelTypes leads to an automatic increase in the Price

Conclusions¶

  1. Having fulfilled all the assumptions of linear regression modeling, we can conclude that the Olsmod2 model is the best fit model for Price Estimation for the new Tech start-up , CARS4U
  2. The Age of a vehicle adversely affects the Price of the vehicle
  3. The total kilometers driven prior to sale of any vehicle has a negative effect on the price
  4. The Owner Type of the vehicle prior clearly impacts on the Price of the vehicle with the first owner type mostly stocked at 82.4%
  5. The Higher the Engine capacity and Brake Horse Power , the higher the Price of the vehicle
  6. Automatic Transmission Types favor Price as against Manual Types which interestingly occupies the inventory of most dealerships at 71.6%
  7. We also discovered that our model validates the neglible impact of the number of seats on Price
  8. Diesel cars are obviously higher priced than their counterparts at 53.5% clearly as a result of higher engine capacity and power
  9. The city of Bangalore has the most priced cars in stock while Mumbai has the highest inventory of mixed priced cars
  10. Car Models of 2015 with 13.1% has more in stock than any other model
  11. The Maruti brand is the most in stock at 20% while the Ford comes leats at a distant 4.8%
